        "## 11.5 The Hessian matrix and second derivative test\n",
        "\n",
        "The second derivative information of a function $f(x,y)$ is organized into the **Hessian matrix**:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "H_f(x,y)=\n",
        "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
        "f_{xx}(x,y) & f_{xy}(x,y)\\\\\n",
        "f_{yx}(x,y) & f_{yy}(x,y)\n",
        "\\end{bmatrix}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "When $f_{xy}=f_{yx}$, this matrix is symmetric. Near a critical point $(a,b)$, the quadratic part of the Taylor approximation is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\frac{1}{2}\n",
        "\\begin{bmatrix}x-a & y-b\\end{bmatrix}\n",
        "H_f(a,b)\n",
        "\\begin{bmatrix}x-a\\\\ y-b\\end{bmatrix}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "So the Hessian describes local curvature.\n",
        "\n",
        "For two-variable functions, define\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D(a,b)=f_{xx}(a,b)f_{yy}(a,b)-[f_{xy}(a,b)]^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the determinant of the Hessian matrix.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-tip}\n",
        "## Second derivative test\n",
        "\n",
        "Suppose $f_x(a,b)=0$, $f_y(a,b)=0$, and the second partial derivatives are continuous near $(a,b)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "- If $D(a,b)>0$ and $f_{xx}(a,b)>0$, then $f$ has a local minimum at $(a,b)$.\n",
        "- If $D(a,b)>0$ and $f_{xx}(a,b)<0$, then $f$ has a local maximum at $(a,b)$.\n",
        "- If $D(a,b)<0$, then $f$ has a saddle point at $(a,b)$.\n",
        "- If $D(a,b)=0$, the test is inconclusive.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why the determinant works\n",
        "\n",
        "The Hessian represents the local quadratic shape. For a symmetric $2\\times 2$ Hessian:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $D>0$ and $f_{xx}>0$ means both principal curvatures are positive, so the surface curves upward in all directions;\n",
        "- $D>0$ and $f_{xx}<0$ means both principal curvatures are negative, so the surface curves downward in all directions;\n",
        "- $D<0$ means one curvature direction is positive and one is negative, so the graph has a saddle shape.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the two-dimensional version of the eigenvalue test for quadratic forms.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Worked example 11.6: classify critical points\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=x^3+y^3-3xy+4.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The first derivatives are\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x=3x^2-3y,\\qquad f_y=3y^2-3x.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Setting them equal to zero gives\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "y=x^2,\\qquad x=y^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Substituting gives $x=x^4$, so $x=0$ or $x=1$. Thus the critical points are\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "(0,0),\\qquad (1,1).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The second derivatives are\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_{xx}=6x,\\qquad f_{yy}=6y,\\qquad f_{xy}=-3.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D(x,y)=36xy-9.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At $(0,0)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D(0,0)=-9<0,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "so $(0,0)$ is a saddle point.\n",
        "\n",
        "At $(1,1)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D(1,1)=27>0,\\qquad f_{xx}(1,1)=6>0,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "so $(1,1)$ is a local minimum. The minimum value is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(1,1)=1+1-3+4=3.\n",
        "$$"
      ],
